Exoplanets

Jake Lee

Introduction

Exoplanets (planets outside our solar system) are an object of great interest in astronomy, both to scientists and the general public. Many science fiction works explore the possibility of life on these planets, and some consider that we may one day be able to colonize new habitable worlds. On the science side, exoplanets provide insight into how our own solar system was formed, as well as clues about the abundance (or lack thereof) of certain elements within the universe.

for i in range(290):
    line = file.readline()
    if line.__contains__("err") or line.__contains__("flag") or line.__contains__("lim"):
        pass
    else:
        print(line[:-1])
file.close()

In [141]:
print(df.columns[70], df.columns[14])

sy_imag pl_msinij

Here, a very interesting relationship is observed. As the radius of the planet increases, the density decreases. In addition, two primary clusters can be observed in the points. This can be attributed to the difference between rocky planets and gas giants. Planets with a large radius tend to be gas giants, and their density is low. Conversely, small gas giants don't form, so smaller planets tend to be rocky, and thus have a higher density. The two clusters observed are rocky planets and gas giants.
